Factors Influencing Term Deposit Subscription

Anthony Mallamaci



West Chester University

Introduction

  • Data comes from Portuguese bank telemarketing campaigns
  • Each row represents one client contact with demographic, financial, and campaign features
  • Target variable:
    • y = 1 client subscribed to a term deposit
    • y = 0 client did not subscribe
  • Two main goals of analysis:
    • Association: Which factors are related to subscription?
    • Prediction: How accurately can we predict who will subscribe?

Agenda

  • Introduction and Data Description
  • Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA)
  • Feature Engineering
  • Linear Regression Model (Balance)
  • Logistic Regression Model (Subscription)
  • Cross-Validation and Model Performance
  • Model Comparison
  • Results and Recommendations
  • Limitations and Final Conclusions

Dataset Overview

  • Key Variables:

    • Demographic Variables
      • age: Client age in years.
      • job: Type of occupation (admin., management, technician, etc.).
      • marital: Marital status (married, divorced/widowed, single).
      • education: Education level (primary, secondary, tertiary, unknown).
    • Financial Variables
      • default: Whether the client has credit in default (yes/no).
      • balance: Average yearly account balance (euros).
      • housing: Whether the client has a housing loan (yes/no).
      • loan: Whether the client has a personal loan (yes/no).
    • Campaign-Related Variables
      • contact: Contact method (telephone, cellular, unknown).
      • day: Day of the month of last contact.
      • month: Month of last contact (jandec).
      • duration: Length of contact in seconds.
      • campaign: Number of contacts in the current campaign.
      • pdays: Days since last contact in a previous campaign (-1 = never contacted).
      • previous: Number of previous contacts.
      • poutcome: Outcome of previous campaign (success, failure, other, unknown).
    • Target Variable
      • y: Client subscribed (yes/no).

  • Sample Size:

    • Over 4,500 observations in the working dataset.

Methods Overview

  • Two approaches used:
    • Logistic regression for predicting term-deposit subscription
    • Linear regression for modeling client balance
  • Logistic Regression
    • Predicts y = 1 (subscribe) or 0 (not subscribe)
    • Key predictors: marital status, education, loans, contact type, month, duration
    • Assumptions checked: independence, no multicollinearity (VIF)
    • Performance assessed with ROC and AUC
  • Linear Regression
    • Predicts average yearly balance
    • Examines effects of marital status and education

EDA

Feature Engineering

  • Encoded target:
    • y = 1 for yes and y = 0 for no.
  • Converted character variables to factors:
    • job, marital, default, housing, loan, contact, month, poutcome.
  • Addressed skewed balance:
    • Performed BoxCox analysis on shifted balance (balance + 3314).
    • Optimal near 0 used log transformation of shifted balance.
  • Created:
    • balance_log as the transformed response for linear regression.

Linear Regression Purpose

  • Question:
    • Do marital status and education help explain a clients average yearly balance?
  • Response:
    • balance (and later balance_log).
  • Predictors:
    • marital (married, single, divorced/widowed)
    • education (primary, secondary, tertiary, unknown)
  • Performed:
    • Backwards step-wise model selection
    • 5-fold cross-validation comparing models with and without interaction.

Regression Results

  • Reference categories:
    • Marital: divorced/widowed
    • Education: primary
  • Findings:
    • Married clients: higher balances than divorced/widowed.
      • Married individuals have 4.4% higher log-balance than divorced individuals on average, controlling for education.
    • Single clients: slightly higher balances (borderline significant).
      • Single individuals have an log-balance 4.37% higher than divorced individuals.
    • Tertiary education: significantly higher balances than primary.
      • Tertiary education is associated with roughly 5% higher log-balance than primary.
    • Secondary and unknown education: not significantly different.
  • Model fit:
    • R 0.009 small portion of balance variation explained.
    • MSE large, indicating substantial unexplained variability.

Logistic Regression Purpose

  • Goals:
    • Identify important predictors of subscription.
    • Build a reduced model that is simpler but still predictive.
  • Response:
    • y (1 = subscribed, 0 = not subscribed).
  • Full model included:
    • Demographics: age, job, marital, education
    • Financial: default, balance, housing, loan
    • Campaign: contact, day, month, duration, campaign, pdays, previous, poutcome
  • Model selection
    • Backward stepwise selection using AIC.
    • Started from the full model and removed weak predictors.
    • Final model balances good fit with interpretability.

Logistic Regression Reduced Model

  • Demographic effects
    • Marital status
      • Married clients have lower odds of subscribing vs.divorced/widowed (p = 0.003).
      • Single clients are not significantly different from divorced/widowed clients.
    • Education
      • Tertiary education increases subscription odds (p = 0.046).
      • Secondary and unknown education levels are not significantly different from primary.
  • Financial factors
    • Housing loan: having a housing loan reduces subscription probability (p = 0.0098).
    • Personal loan: strong negative effect as clients with a personal loan are roughly 47.2% less likely to subscribe (p = 0.0012).
  • Contact information
    • Unknown contact type dramatically decreases subscription odds by 76.7% (p < 0.0001).
    • Telephone vs.cellular: no meaningful difference (p 0.97).
  • Timing variables (month effects)
    • Some months differ significantly from the reference month:
      • Higher likelihood: March, October, September (positive coefficients).
      • Lower likelihood: January, July, November (negative coefficients).
    • Suggests seasonal patterns in client responsiveness.
  • Call & campaign variables
    • Duration of last call is a strong positive predictor (p < 0.0001).
    • Number of campaign contacts slightly reduces subscription probability (p 0.010) diminishing returns from repeated calls.
    • Previous campaign success is the strongest positive predictor increasing the odds of subscribing by over 10 times that of a previous campaign failure (p < 0.0001).

Model Performance

  • Goal: evaluate how well our models predict client balance (linear regression) and subscription (logistic regression).
  • Use:
    • 5-fold cross-validation and MSE for the linear regression models.
    • ROC curves and AUC for the logistic regression models.
  • This tells us whether the models are reliable enough to guide marketing decisions and which specification performs best.

Linear Regression: 5-Fold Cross-Validation

  • Two models for balance:
    • M1: marital + education (main effects only)
    • M2: marital * education (adds interaction)
  • Average MSEs are very similar and the curves across folds nearly overlap.
  • Interpretation Adding the interaction yields no meaningful improvement, so the simpler main-effects model is preferred for prediction.

Logistic Regression: Full Model Performance

  • Test AUC = 0.8757 model correctly ranks a random subscriber above a random non-subscriber about 87.6% of the time (strong discrimination).
  • Optimal cutoff probability 0.094:
    • Probabilities 0.094 predict subscribe.

Logistic Regression: Cross-Validation & Model Choice

  • 5-fold CV on the reduced model (poutcome + month + marital + contact + duration) gives AUCs between 0.87 and 0.92 (mean 0.89), showing stable performance across folds.
  • On the test set:
    • Model 1 (full): AUC = 0.8757
    • Model 2 (reduced): AUC = 0.8696, optimal cutoff 0.091
      • Probabilities above 0.091 are predicted as yes
  • The difference is small, but Model 1 consistently shows slightly higher AUC, however I selected the reduced logistic model as the final model because its AUC (0.8696) is nearly identical to the full model (0.8757), yet it uses far fewer predictors.

Predicitive Model

  • Two hypothetical clients were evaluated using the final logistic model:
    • Client 1: -Single, tertiary education, good balance, no loans, cellular contact, March, longer duration, success in previous campaign.
      • Predicted to subscribe (y = 1).
    • Client 2: -Married, secondary education, lower balance, housing and personal loans, unknown contact, October, shorter call, prior failure. -Predicted to not subscribe (y = 0).
  • Shows how model can support targeted marketing.

Recommendations

  • Focus marketing efforts on:
    • Clients with tertiary education.
    • Clients with prior successful campaigns.
    • Months with historically higher success (March, October, September).
  • Operational strategies:
    • Allow sufficient call duration to engage clients.
    • Avoid excessive contacts (high campaign values reduce odds).
    • Improve data collection to reduce unknown contact and poutcome categories.

Limitations

  • Linear regression:
    • Balance remains skewed even after transformation; conclusions should be interpreted cautiously.
    • R is low; many other factors likely influence balance.
  • Logistic regression:
    • Duration is an outcome of the call, not a pre-campaign feature.
      • It happens during the call, so it cant be used for true pre-call targeting.
    • Data from a single bank and time period; limited generalizability.
      • Findings may not apply to other banks, regions, or time periods.

Overall Conclusions

  • Linear regression:
    • Marital status and education are statistically related to balance, but explain only a small fraction of variability.
  • Logistic regression:
    • Final reduced model achieves strong predictive performance (AUC 0.87).
    • Key drivers of term deposit subscription:
      • Call duration
      • Previous campaign success
      • Certain months
      • Loan and housing status
      • Marital status and contact method
  • The final logistic model offers a useful, interpretable tool for targeting future marketing campaigns.
